Key Dates May , : S 3 online submission portal opens (stay tuned for it here!) June : Last date to submit entries August : Finalists announced September : S 3 finals event Eligibility All US high school students are invited to Entries Submitted stories should be original (even when describing other scientists’ work, the account should reflect the student’s voice). Entries prepared with the help of generative AI systems (like ChatGPT) or adapting other sources are not disallowed but need to be marked as Each entry should be roughly words long, capable of being narrated in 5 minutes or Students can submit multiple entries, and joint entries are Prizes Grand prize: $1000 cash award to writer(s) : $500 cash award to writer(s) Audience choice: $500 cash award to writer(s) finalists: $200 cash award to each finalist(s) + lunch at Harvard MIT or Cambridge biotech tech company All entrants: A ScienceStorySlam + other fun swag! Judging Process : Scientists engineers from MIT Harvard + biotech tech companies Finals: Celebrated scientists engineers + storytellers Tips Judging will NOT focus on writing quality, or if you advance to the Finals, public speaking experience for sharing your story Instead, our judges will look for a compelling story that integrates concepts from science, technology, engineering or math (STEM), or shows how you have engaged with science and how it has impacted To help you brainstorm some ideas, here are some sample prompts you could answer with your story: Is there a fictional world you can imagine which illustrates a STEM concept? What is the origin story of how a scientific or technical advancement was made? How did you get interested in STEM in your own life? Questions?
